>How is pedal effort compared to a stock '68-'70 with drum brakes?

The disc brakes require far more pressure to stop.

>I
>know that some of the euro busses came with disk brakes and no
>booster.  I wonder if having the non-functional booster in the system
>would greatly increase the effort required to stop the bus?  Anyone
>out there with disk brakes and no booster care to comment?

Like I said, turn off the the engine and try to stop in a 71-79 bus. It's much harder.

>I ask because I am in the process of upgrading my '69 to disk brakes,
>and I am not planning to use the booster.  My feeling is that the bus
>won't be any harder to stop than it is now, and I don't have a problem
>with the level of effort now.

It will be harder. So much so that this will probably be an overall braking downgrade although just slightly above Flintstones.

